<paragraph blockId="2.[812,1420,1348,1548]" pageId="2" pageNumber="211">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,1348,1372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="211">Identification.</emphasis>
The Giant Anteater is the only species of genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[882,1051,1383,1407]" class="Mammalia" family="Myrmecophagidae" genus="Myrmecophaga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pilosa" pageId="2" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[882,1051,1383,1407]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="211">Myrmecophaga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Its large size, long and furry tail, the large black stripe running from its throat towards its back, bordered by a thin white stripe, and its long and pointy snout make this species clearly distinct from any other in the region.
</paragraph>
